    {
      "title": "Prepositions and the Genitive Case",
      "titleArabic": "حُرُوفُ الْجَرِّ",
      "content": [
        "Arabic prepositions (hurūf al-jarr) are particles that indicate location, direction, or relationship. The noun following a preposition always takes the genitive case (majrūr), marked by kasra (-i).",
        "Common prepositions include فِي (in), مِنْ (from), إِلَى (to), عَلَى (on), and مَعَ (with). These are essential for describing where things and people are."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Nouns after prepositions take the genitive case (-i ending)",
        "فِي (in) - for location inside something",
        "مِنْ (from) - for origin or source",
        "إِلَى (to) - for direction or destination",
        "عَلَى (on) - for being on top of something"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "فِي الْبَيْتِ", "english": "in the house" },
        { "arabic": "مِنَ الْمَسْجِدِ", "english": "from the mosque" },
        { "arabic": "إِلَى الْمَدْرَسَةِ", "english": "to the school" },
        { "arabic": "عَلَى الطَّاوِلَةِ", "english": "on the table" }
      ]
    }
  ],
